Skewness interpretation¶

If the peak of the distribution is on the left of the average value (as in this scenario), portraying a positive skewness in the distribution, it means that many houses are being sold for less than the average value. This could be for many reasons and we should investigate that. If the peak of the distributed data is on the right of the average value, that means a negative skew. This means that the houses are being sold for more than the average value.

Kurtosis interpretation¶

Kurtosis is about the tails of the distribution. It is used to describe the extreme values in one versus the other tail. It is actually the measure of outliers present in the distribution. High kurtosis in a data set is an indicator that data has heavy tails or outliers. If there is a high kurtosis (as in this case), then, we need to investigate why do we have so many outliers. It indicates a lot of things, maybe wrong data entry or other things.

The 2 values indicate that the TARGET variable is pretty skewed. A common procedure to deal with that and reduce this effect is to apply a log scale that usually allows to reach better performance in regression tasks.

1.3 Dealing with missing values¶

The first thing that should be done when dealing with missing value is to try understanding why data are missing and which kind of missing values we are dealing with. In particular, the types of missing values could be:

  • missing completely at random (MCAR);
  • missing at random (MAR);
  • not missing at random (NMAR);
    In the last scenario, the first thing that should be done is to come back to the source of data and investigating more on why these data are missing (i.e. consider a survey about Incomes, people with high Incomes could be less prone of communicating the Information and therefore Imputing the missing value with mean or median could be inappropriate). Unfortunately I don't have further information on how the data is been collected so I will consider the missing values as MCAR/CAR.

Apart from that, you could deal with missing values in different ways:

  • you could apply a list-wise deletion to all the instances that have a missing value, but this could reduce too much the size of the dataset, so It Is worth only for small percentages of missing values. Eventually you could delete only the instances that present a percentage of missing values (over the different attributes of the Instance) that Is higher than a threshold (I.e. 50%).
  • you could decide to delete an entire column/attribute/feature If the percentage of missing values for that attribute Is higher than a threshold;
  • finally, you could decide to Impute the missing values using for example the mean or the median (that are the most common Imputation techniques because they are quick to Implement and work well). You should preferer the median over the mean when there are several outliers (mean is sensitive to outliers) or first remove the outliers and consider them as missing values. - there are also more sophisticated Imputation techniques: for example you could use a regression model to Impute the missing variables or you could replace It with a random chosen value from an Instance from the population that Is similar to the Instance on which we are performing Imputation (this technique is called hot deck imputation). The ones mentioned above are some example of 'single Imputation' techniques but there also exist 'multiple imputation' techniques, a little bit more sophisticated, that allow to assign multiple possible values to the missing attribute and are less biased.

Some remarks:
Imputation Is useful because the major part of the Machine Learning algorithms cannot deal with missing values but there are some other algorithms (i.e. Nave Bayes) that can also deal with missing values.
You could also keep track of which value Is been Imputed and which not and supplying this Information to the algorithms with a binary variable (Imputed/not Imputed).

Now, how we impute the missing values for the numerical features? As discussed before, mean or median imputation, are simple but effective techniques. We choose to use the median (more robust to outliers) because, even if we previously replaced some examples that we considered as outliers, the distibution of the variables still shows an important Kurtosis index.

Imputation of missing values for numerical features¶

When imputing the missing values, we will keep track of which variable is been imputed. Therefore we add a column for each input feature in the dataset that will consist in a binary variable (1 if the variable is imputed, 0 otherwise).

In [28]:
#create a column 'variableName_imputed' for each variable in NUM_FEATURES
print(train.shape)
for var in NUM_FEATURES:
    var_imputed = var + "_imputed"
    train[var_imputed] = pd.DataFrame(np.zeros((train.shape[0], 1)))
print(train.shape)

(25190, 39)
In [29]:
for var in NUM_FEATURES:
    print(str(var) + ":")
    print("Count before imputing: " + str(train[var].count()))
    computed_median = train[var].median(skipna = True)
    #keep track of the variables that will be imputed
    var_imputed = var + "_imputed"
    train[var_imputed] = train.apply(lambda x : (1 if math.isnan(x[var])  else  0),axis=1)
    train[var] = train.apply(lambda x : (computed_median if math.isnan(x[var])  else  x[var]),axis=1)
    print("Count after imputing: " + str(train[var].count()))
    print()

How can be notice from the picture above, there is a relationship between the 'condition' of the appartment and the 'building_year'. In partioular we can see that:

  • NEW or LIKE NEW appartments ('Erstbezug' or 'Neuwertig') (red color) are quite predominant when building_year >=2010 (more or less);
  • REFINED or ELEGANT appartments ('Gepflegt') (blue color) appear more often when 1990 <= building_year < 2010;
  • MODERN ('Modernisiert') (green color) or 'renovated' ('Erstbezug nach Sanierung', 'Vollstanding renoviert', 'Saniert') (yellow color) appear more often when building_year < 1990.

Therefore, rather than impute the missing values for 'condition' simply with the mode, we could:

  • set it as 'Neuwertig' (that overll appears more often than 'Erstbezug') when building_year >=2010;
  • set it as 'Gepflegt' (actual mode of 'condition') when 1975 < building_year < 2010;
  • set it as 'Modernisiert' (that overall appers more often than 'Erstbezug nach Sanierung' or 'Vollstanding renoviert') when building_year <= 1975;

In [44]:
def get_condition_from_building_year(year):
    ''''Neuwertig' when building_year >=2010;
    'Gepflegt' when 1975 < building_year < 2010;
    'Modernisiert'  when building_year <= 1975;'''
    if (year<2010):
        if(year<= 1975):
            return 'Modernisiert'
        else:
            return 'Gepflegt'
    else:
        return 'Neuwertig'

def get_street(zip_code, district_id, zone_id):
    """retrieve street mode of the instances with given 'zip_code', 'district_id' and 'zone_id' 
    in case of exception return the default mode"""
    try:
        mode = train[(train.zip_code == x['zip_code']) & (train.district_id == x['district_id']) & (train.zone_id == x['zone_id'])][var].mode()[0]
    except:
        mode = train['street'].mode()[0]
    return mode

The descriptions contain a lot of information. Unfortunately the information is unstructured and we need to find a way to extract structured relevant information.
When dealing with text there are several possible approaches:

  • use a bag of word model where we keep tract of which word is contained in the text and wich not
  • use word embedings and map words in the text to vectors.

Unfortunately these approaches have 2 main problems in this context:
1) using these approaches the number of input features will drastically increase (bag of word generates a sparse vector with the dimension of the vocaboulary size, word embedding use vectors which common dimension is 300)
2) the text is in german (not in english) and a lot of libriries for the mentioned approaches are available only in english (i.e. text preprocessing libraries used for word embedding are difficult to find for languages that are not english, the pre-trained wort embeddings algorithms are trained on english text corpus).

Therefore, we need a way to extract relevant information from the text, without increasing too much the number of input features.

The fist thing we can do is to keep track of wich instance contains a description and which not:

A possible solution for the problem mentioned above is:

  • we find the words contained in the descriptions that are more discriminative for high or low 'price_m2'.
  • we select the n (i.e. 10) most discriminative words and we use n binary variables (word1_contained, ..., wordn_contained) to keep track of which description contains these words.

In this way we use an approach similar to bag of word models but we limit the additional number of features to n (rather than the entire vocaboulary size)

First of all we vectorize all the words contained in the description. We use TfidfVectorizer by sklearn that uses spars matrices (faster computation).

How can we notice, the vocauboulary size is huge and we cannot consider all the possible contained words. Therefore, we use a chi-squared test to select the most discriminative words. Note: The chi-squared test works with classification, therefore we use a dummy variable 'above_average' that keeps track of which instance has a TARGET VARIABLE value above the average. In this way, the chi-squared test finds the most discriminative words for values of the TARGET above or below the average.

In [68]:

train['above_average'] = train.apply(lambda x : (1 if x[LOG_TARGET]>mean else  0),axis=1)

In [76]:
def get_days(date_string):
    """return the number of days between start_date and date_string"""
    start_date = datetime.strptime('2018-01-01', '%Y-%m-%d').date()
    date = datetime.strptime(date_string, '%Y-%m-%d').date()
    delta = date - start_date
    return delta.days

1.4 Recap:¶

Let's do a recap of what we did with the training set.
For the numerical variabes:

  • we tried to detect outliers (i.e. 'num_rooms' sometime has a value of 170 that is not feasible for and apartment) and replace them with the 95% quantile;
  • we analyzed the distribution of missing values;
  • we checked if we could impute 'num_bedrooms' using the eq. num_rooms = num_bathrooms + num_bedrooms, but we had to exclude this assumption;
  • we impute the missing values with the median.
  • we kept track of which variable we imputed.

For the categorical variables:

  • we analyzed the missing value distribution;
  • we analized the distribution of each categorical variable;
  • we dropped 'property_type_id', 'market_type', 'city_id' because they contain always the same value;
  • we imputed the variables 'appartment_type' with the mode;
  • we noticed a relationship between the variable 'condition' and the variable 'building_year' and we used it to imputed the missing values accordingly;
  • similarly, we noticed a relationship between the variable 'interior_quality' and the variable 'building_year' and we used it to imputed the missing values accordingly;
  • we imputed 'district_id' with the mode computed over the instances with the same 'zip_code' of the instance to impute
  • 'zone_id' with the mode computed over the instances with the same 'zip_code' and 'district_id' of the instance to impute:
  • 'street' with the mode computed over the instances with the same 'zip_code', 'district_id' and 'zone_id' of the instance to impute
  • we kept track of the variables that have been imputed

For text the variable 'description':

  • we kept track of which instance have or does not have a description;
  • we tried to find the most dicriminative words using a chi-squared test and the variable 'above_average' without drammatically increase the number of input variables;
  • we kept track, for each of the words we found (8 in total), wich instance contains the word in the description

Finally:

  • we replaced some outliers in 'num_days' with the medin
  • we converted 'posted_at' in the number of days between '2018-01-01' (start date) and posted_at_date
  • we converted 'ended_at' in the sum of days 'posted_at' + 'num_days'
  • we dropped 'street_number'

Now, before further proceding with the analysis, let's apply the same procedure to the test.
Note: When imputing the missing values on the test, we use the median/mode computed over the train (otherwise we would cheat!)

The problem is that in total we have 18 binary features of this type (see below).
Can we select, in some way, only the most important ones?
The answer is yes and, similarly of what we did with the most discriminative words inside the description, we use a chi-squared test.
This is an example of feature selection/elimination . Reducing the number of considered features (filtering out the less relevants) help to reach better performance and reduce the probability of overfitting.
There are several techniques in order to perform feature selection but let's skip this discussion for now.

Note: 'zip_code' has a huge number of distinct values and has to be treated as a categorical variable. Therefore it is not suitable for the training of the algorithms because we should apply One Hot Encoding and produce as many binary features as the number of unique zip codes. We could also try to use a chi-squared test in order to find the most relevant zip codes but it would be not so effective with so many distinct value.
Considering the fact that we are already taking into account spatial information thanks to 'latidude', 'longitude', 'radius', etc. we could ignore the 'zip_code' variable and drop it.

Same considerations can be done for the variables 'distict_id' and 'zone_id' that identify a sub_area inside the zip_code.
Moreover, if we eliminate 'zip_code' these variables loose meaning (2 apartments with same 'district_id' can be in different areas with different 'zip_code'). Therefore we drop also these 2 variables.
Same problem arises also with the categorical variable 'street' to which applying a chi-squared test in order to find the most discriminative Streets would be possible but expensive (too many distinct values of 'street'). Therefore we choose to drop also the variable 'street' for now.

2 Regression Model¶

2.1 Introduction¶

In this section we will try some of the regression algorithms from sklear.
In order to not make the notebook too long and save time, we will try just few of the available algorithms.
In particoular we will play with the following models:

  • Linear Regression: it would eventually give as a baseiline;
  • Lasso and Ridge Regression: it would be interesting to check how l1 and l2 penalizations works in this context;
  • Decision Tree regressor: intuitive but powerful algorithm;
  • Random Forest: an example of ensemble of decision trees in order to check if the performance improves with respect to single decision trees;
  • simple Neural Network - Multi Layer Perceptron.

Each algorithm is further discussed later. When possible, we will perform hyper parameter tuning.

We will evaluate the different models with 10 fold crossvalidation keeping into account the following metrics:

  • Means Squared Error (MSE);
  • r2 that describe how good the algorithms perform with respect to predicting the mean. (from sklearn documentation: R^2 (coefficient of determination) regression score function. Best possible score is 1.0 and it can be negative (because the model can be arbitrarily worse). A constant model that always predicts the expected value of y, disregarding the input features, would get a R^2 score of 0.0. )

We try to predict LOG_TARGET (normalized). In case we need later to come back to the original TARGET variable we can easily apply the inverse function.

Before trying the different models, we normalize the data. This is a common procedure that is usefull for some of the algorithms listed above (all except DT and RF) because they are sensible to scaling.
We use the library function StandarScaler by Sklearn.

2.3 Crossvalidation¶

In [192]:
#import libraries
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_validate
import sklearn.metrics as m
from sklearn.metrics import  make_scorer

#define score metrics
r2_scorer = make_scorer(m.r2_score)
mean_squared_error_scorer = make_scorer(m.mean_squared_error)

scoring = {'r2': r2_scorer, 'mean_squared_error': mean_squared_error_scorer}

Let's define a function to perform our procedure:

In [193]:
#define function
def crossValidate(reg, verbose = True, scoring = scoring, FEATURES = FEATURES):
    #compute scores with 10 fold CrossValidation
    scores = cross_validate(reg, train[FEATURES], train[LOG_TARGET], scoring=scoring,cv=10, return_estimator=True)
    
    #retrieve test metrics
    test_MSE = scores['test_mean_squared_error'].mean()
    test_r2 = scores['test_r2'].mean()

    #compute also training metrics
    reg.fit(train[FEATURES], train[LOG_TARGET])
    train_predictions = reg.predict(train[FEATURES])
    train_r2 = m.r2_score(train[LOG_TARGET], train_predictions)
    train_mean_squared_error = m.mean_squared_error(train[LOG_TARGET], train_predictions)
    #print(scores.keys())
    if verbose:
        print(reg)
        print()

        #scores
        print("training time: " + str(round(scores['fit_time'].mean(),2)))
        print("prediction time: " + str(round(scores['score_time'].mean(),2)))
        print()

        print("train_mean_squared_error : " + str(round(train_mean_squared_error,5)))
        print("average test mean_squared_error : " + str(round(test_MSE,5)))
        print()

        print("train_r2_score : " + str(round(train_r2,3)))
        print("average test_r2: " + str(round(test_r2,3)))
    return {'predictor': reg, 'train_MSE' : train_mean_squared_error, 'train_r2': train_r2, 'test_MSE': test_MSE, 'test_r2': test_r2 }

How can be noticed, Ridge Regression is not able to learn and it overfitts (as Linear Regression but in a smaller extend). The results suggest that an appropriate Feature selection procedure should be applyied. The 'best' results are obtained when alpha is bigger (stronger penalization) but we cannot consider these results 'good' if compared with the results of Lasso.

Decision Trees:¶

Is interestinng to try decision trees algorithms because:

  • they are able to capture non-linear relationships between input features and target;
  • they can deal with highly correlated features;
  • they perform feature selection selecting the best feature to use in a branch-node thanks to the 'information gain' criterion.

How we noticed before, the problem of single decision trees is that they tend to overfitt when we increase the depth.
For this purpose we can try to use ensemble methods (i.e. Random Forest) that thanks to averaging voting they should reduce overfitting and increase the performance.

2.5 Future work¶

As we stated before, we tried just few of the available regression algorithms but we should experiment with more of them.
For example we just used an example of ensemble (Random Forest) but we should try out also other of them that works differently (see GradientTreeBosting, Adaboost, etc.).
What about KNN, SVM, Naive Bayes, etc? We should try them as well.

We saw how some algorithms is not able to learn and completely overfitt.
Therefore, another important thing that we should do is to try different subsets of features (what about removing the features in SHOULD_REMOVE list or considering only the most important binary features?!) and apply feature selection.
We saw some intrinsic feature selection procedure (l1 penalization with Lasso and information gain with Decision Trees) but there are other possible approaches (see PCA, backward or forward feature selection. etc.).

That's all for now!
